Project Overview:
This project focuses on forecasting monthly U.S. coking coal export volumes using the Adaptive Neuro-Fuzzy Inference System (ANFIS).
The study compares two neuro-fuzzy forecasting models: a baseline model using historical observations only and an enhanced model that incorporates quarterly and annual seasonal components. 
The workflow includes time series analysis, autocorrelation assessment, feature selection, data preprocessing, ANFIS model training, and comparative forecasting accuracy evaluation using the Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE).

Tools:
- MATLAB
- ANFIS Editor
- Fuzzy Logic Toolbox
- Time Series Analysis

Methods Applied:
- Autocorrelation Function (ACF) Analysis
- Lag Selection
- Seasonal Feature Engineering
- Training and Test Data Split (5:1)
- Neuro-Fuzzy Modeling (ANFIS)
- Forecast Accuracy Evaluation

Project Workflow:
1. Analysis of historical monthly export data.
2. Identification of significant lag variables using autocorrelation analysis.
3. Consideration of quarterly and yearly seasonal components.
4. Preparation of training and testing datasets.
5. Training of a neuro-fuzzy forecasting model.
6. Evaluation of forecasting performance on unseen data.

Results:
The project compares two ANFIS-based forecasting models: one using only historical observations and another incorporating quarterly and annual seasonal components.
Performance evaluation using the Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE) demonstrated a substantial improvement when seasonality was included. 
The seasonal model achieved a **MAPE of 67.6%**, compared to **406.9%** for the baseline model.
The results confirm that incorporating seasonal information significantly enhances forecasting accuracy and improves the predictive capability of neuro-fuzzy models for time series analysis.
